{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775870803284,"sessionID":"ses_285daca2dffetuopp54L7bgIWw","part":{"id":"prt_d7a25fd43001KHncrGvDXqqnXr","messageID":"msg_d7a25f503001pWUPjmi0giDYfn","sessionID":"ses_285daca2dffetuopp54L7bgIWw","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_tool-7f40a38e2f5148b99d7cb4de9f157f06","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Delta Specification: AR-023 — CLI invoke/status Commands\n2: \n3: ## Module: `cmd/cli`\n4: \n5: ## Language: Python\n6: \n7: ## Size: M\n8: \n9: ## Delta Overview\n10: \n11: Add the `invoke` and `status` commands to the AgentCube CLI for sending payloads to deployed agents and checking their deployment status, supporting both AgentCube (AgentRuntime CR) and standard Kubernetes (Deployment/Service) providers.\n12: \n13: ---\n14: \n15: ## REQ-001: Invoke command initialization\n16: \n17: ### Requirement: Invoke command registration and default options\n18: \n19: System SHALL provide an `invoke` command that sends JSON payloads to deployed agent endpoints with configurable options.\n20: \n21: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n22: - Command name: `invoke`\n23: - Supports workspace path specification\n24: - Supports JSON payload specification\n25: - Supports custom HTTP headers\n26: - Supports provider selection (agentcube/k8s)\n27: - Provides verbose mode for detailed logging\n28: \n29: **Scenarios:**\n30: \n31: #### Scenario 1.1: Command registration and default options\n32: - **GIVEN** the AgentCube CLI Typer application is initialized\n33: - **WHEN** the user runs `kubectl-agentcube invoke` without options\n34: - **THEN** the system SHALL use these defaults:\n35:   - `workspace`: `\".\"` (current directory)\n36:   - `payload`: `\"{}\"` (empty JSON object)\n37:   - `header_list`: `None`\n38:   - `provider`: `\"agentcube\"`\n39:   - `verbose`: `False`\n40: \n41: #### Scenario 1.2: Command option validation\n42: - **GIVEN** the user provides CLI options\n43: - **WHEN** options include `--workspace`, `--payload`, `--header`, `--provider`, `--verbose`\n44: - **THEN** the system SHALL accept all valid option values:\n45:   - `workspace`: string path to workspace directory\n46:   - `payload`: JSON-formatted string\n47:   - `header_list`: list of strings in \"key:value\" format\n48:   - `provider`: string (\"agentcube\" or \"k8s\")\n49:   - `verbose`: boolean flag\n50: \n51: ---\n52: \n53: ## REQ-002: Payload validation and parsing\n54: \n55: ### Requirement: JSON payload validation\n56: \n57: System SHALL validate the payload format before invocation and provide clear error messages.\n58: \n59: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n60: - Validates JSON syntax before sending\n61: - Rejects invalid JSON with clear error message\n62: - Supports complex nested JSON structures\n63: - Exits with code 1 on invalid payload\n64: \n65: **Scenarios:**\n66: \n67: #### Scenario 2.1: Valid JSON payload\n68: - **GIVEN** the user provides a valid JSON payload string\n69: - **WHEN** `--payload '{\"query\": \"What is AI?\", \"context\": [\"ML\"]}'` is parsed\n70: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n71:   - Successfully parse it into a Python dictionary\n72:   - Pass it to the runtime\n73:   - Continue with invocation\n74: \n75: #### Scenario 2.2: Invalid JSON payload\n76: - **GIVEN** the user provides an invalid JSON payload\n77: - **WHEN** `--payload '{invalid json}'` is parsed\n78: - **THEN** the CLI SHALL:\n79:   - Print \"Invalid JSON payload\" in red\n80:   - Exit with code `1`\n81:   - NOT call `InvokeRuntime.invoke` or `_handle_error`\n82: \n83: #### Scenario 2.3: Empty payload default\n84: - **GIVEN** the user omits the `--payload` option\n85: - **WHEN** the command runs with default payload `\"{}\"`\n86: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n87:   - Parse `\"{}\"` as an empty dictionary\n88:   - Pass empty dictionary to runtime\n89: \n90: #### Scenario 2.4: Complex nested payload\n91: - **GIVEN** the user provides a complex nested JSON structure\n92: - **WHEN** `--payload '{\"messages\": [{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"Hello\"}], \"temperature\": 0.7, \"max_tokens\": 100}'` is parsed\n93: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n94:   - Preserve the full structure\n95:   - Pass it to the runtime\n96: \n97: ---\n98: \n99: ## REQ-003: Header format validation\n100: \n101: ### Requirement: Custom header validation\n102: \n103: System SHALL validate custom header format and provide clear error messages for malformed headers.\n104: \n105: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n106: - Validates header format contains at least one colon\n107: - Rejects invalid format with clear error message\n108: - Supports headers with colons in values\n109: - Supports multiple header specifications\n110: \n111: **Scenarios:**\n112: \n113: #### Scenario 3.1: Valid header format\n114: - **GIVEN** the user provides correctly formatted headers\n115: - **WHEN** parsing `--header 'Authorization: Bearer token'` and `--header 'Content-Type: application/json'`\n116: - **THEN** each header SHALL be:\n117:   - Split at the first `:` into key and value\n118: \n119: #### Scenario 3.2: Invalid header without colon\n120: - **GIVEN** the user provides a header string without a colon separator\n121: - **WHEN** `--header 'InvalidHeader'` is parsed\n122: - **THEN** the CLI SHALL:\n123:   - Print \"Header must be in 'key:value' format\" in red\n124:   - Exit with code `1`\n125: \n126: #### Scenario 3.3: Header with multiple colons\n127: - **GIVEN** the user provides a header with colons in the value\n128: - **WHEN** `--header 'Authorization: Bearer:token:with:colons'` is parsed\n129: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n130:   - Split only at the first `:`\n131:   - key = `\"Authorization\"`\n132:   - value = `\"Bearer:token:with:colons\"`\n133: \n134: #### Scenario 3.4: Empty header value\n135: - **GIVEN** the user provides a header with an empty value\n136: - **WHEN** `--header 'X-Custom-Header:'` is parsed\n137: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n138:   - key = `\"X-Custom-Header\"`\n139:   - value = `\"\"` (empty string)\n140: \n141: #### Scenario 3.5: Multiple header specifications\n142: - **GIVEN** the user needs to pass multiple custom headers\n143: - **WHEN** the command is `invoke --header 'Authorization: Bearer token1' --header 'X-Custom-Header: value'`\n144: - **THEN** `header_list` SHALL be `['Authorization: Bearer token1', 'X-Custom-Header: value']`\n145: \n146: ---\n147: \n148: ## REQ-004: Session header management\n149: \n150: ### Requirement: Automatic session ID header injection\n151: \n152: System SHALL automatically add the session ID header when metadata contains a `session_id`.\n153: \n154: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n155: - Automatically adds session header when session_id exists\n156: - Does not add session header when session_id is missing\n157: - Allows custom header to override metadata session_id\n158: - Uses correct header name spelling\n159: \n160: **Scenarios:**\n161: \n162: #### Scenario 4.1: Session ID from metadata\n163: - **GIVEN** the agent metadata contains `session_id: \"abc-123-def\"`\n164: - **WHEN** `InvokeRuntime.invoke` runs with this metadata\n165: - **THEN** the HTTP request SHALL include:\n166:   - Header `X-Agentcube-Session-Id: abc-123-def`\n167: \n168: #### Scenario 4.2: No session ID in metadata\n169: - **GIVEN** the agent metadata does not contain a `session_id` field\n170: - **WHEN** `InvokeRuntime.invoke` runs\n171: - **THEN** the HTTP request SHALL NOT include:\n172:   - The session header\n173: \n174: #### Scenario 4.3: Session ID override with custom header\n175: - **GIVEN** the metadata has `session_id: \"abc-123\"`\n176: - **WHEN** the user provides `--header 'X-Agentcube-Session-Id: custom-session'`\n177: - **THEN** the custom header value SHALL:\n178:   - Take precedence over the metadata session ID\n179: \n180: ---\n181: \n182: ## REQ-005: Workspace path resolution\n183: \n184: ### Requirement: Path resolution for invoke\n185: \n186: System SHALL resolve the workspace path relative to the current working directory.\n187: \n188: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n189: - Resolves relative paths correctly\n190: - Handles absolute paths correctly\n191: - Uses current directory as default\n192: \n193: **Scenarios:**\n194: \n195: #### Scenario 5.1: Relative workspace path\n196: - **GIVEN** the user provides `-f ./my-agent`\n197: - **WHEN** the workspace path is resolved\n198: - **THEN** it SHALL be:\n199:   - Resolved to `{cwd}/my-agent`\n200: \n201: #### Scenario 5.2: Absolute workspace path\n202: - **GIVEN** the user provides `-f /absolute/path/to/agent`\n203: - **WHEN** the workspace path is resolved\n204: - **THEN** it SHALL remain:\n205:   - `/absolute/path/to/agent`\n206: \n207: #### Scenario 5.3: Default workspace path\n208: - **GIVEN** the user omits the `-f` option\n209: - **WHEN** the workspace path is resolved\n210: - **THEN** it SHALL be:\n211:   - The current working directory `\".\"`\n212: \n213: ---\n214: \n215: ## REQ-006: Provider-specific invocation\n216: \n217: ### Requirement: Provider-based routing\n218: \n219: System SHALL route invocation requests to the appropriate endpoint based on the `provider` parameter.\n220: \n221: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n222: - Routes to AgentRuntime CR endpoint for agentcube provider\n223: - Routes to K8s service endpoint for k8s provider\n224: - Rewrites URL correctly for AgentRuntime invocations\n225: - Uses Router URL when available\n226: \n227: **Scenarios:**\n228: \n229: #### Scenario 6.1: AgentCube provider (default)\n230: - **GIVEN** `provider` is `\"agentcube\"` (default)\n231: - **WHEN** the agent is deployed as an AgentRuntime CR\n232: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n233:   - Load metadata and check for `k8s_deployment.type == \"AgentRuntime\"`\n234:   - Rewrite the URL to `{base}/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/agent-runtimes/{agent_name}/invocations/`\n235:   - Include session headers if present\n236: \n237: #### Scenario 6.2: Kubernetes provider\n238: - **GIVEN** `provider` is `\"k8s\"`\n239: - **WHEN** the agent is deployed as a standard K8s Deployment/Service\n240: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n241:   - Use the service URL from metadata (e.g., `http://localhost:{node_port}`)\n242:   - NOT rewrite the URL to the AgentRuntime invocation path\n243:   - Direct POST to the agent's endpoint\n244: \n245: #### Scenario 6.3: AgentCube provider with Router URL\n246: - **GIVEN** `provider` is `\"agentcube\"`\n247: - **WHEN** metadata contains `router_url`\n248: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n249:   - Use the Router URL for invocation\n250:   - Format as `{router_url}/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/agent-runtimes/{agent_name}/invocations/`\n251: \n252: ---\n253: \n254: ## REQ-007: Invoke prerequisites validation\n255: \n256: ### Requirement: Pre-invocation validation\n257: \n258: System SHALL validate that all prerequisites are met before attempting invocation.\n259: \n260: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n261: - Validates agent is published (has agent_id)\n262: - Validates metadata file exists\n263: - Validates workspace path exists\n264: - Validates provider value is valid\n265: \n266: **Scenarios:**\n267: \n268: #### Scenario 7.1: Agent not published\n269: - **GIVEN** the workspace metadata lacks `agent_id`\n270: - **WHEN** `invoke` is called\n271: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n272:   - Raise an error indicating the agent must be published first\n273: \n274: #### Scenario 7.2: Missing metadata file\n275: - **GIVEN** the workspace directory exists\n276: - **WHEN** it has no `agent_metadata.yaml` (or fallbacks)\n277: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n278:   - Raise an error indicating metadata file is missing\n279: \n280: #### Scenario 7.3: Invalid workspace path\n281: - **GIVEN** the specified workspace path does not exist\n282: - **WHEN** `invoke` is called\n283: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n284:   - Raise a `ValueError` indicating the directory does not exist\n285: \n286: #### Scenario 7.4: Invalid provider value\n287: - **GIVEN** the user provides an invalid provider value\n288: - **WHEN** `--provider invalid-provider` is parsed\n289: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n290:   - Validate and reject the provider value\n291: \n292: ---\n293: \n294: ## REQ-008: Invoke response handling\n295: \n296: ### Requirement: Response processing and display\n297: \n298: System SHALL handle and display invocation responses appropriately.\n299: \n300: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n301: - Displays successful responses in readable format\n302: - Displays error responses with details\n303: - Handles network timeouts gracefully\n304: - Formats JSON responses properly\n305: \n306: **Scenarios:**\n307: \n308: #### Scenario 8.1: Successful invocation\n309: - **GIVEN** the agent endpoint returns a successful response (2xx)\n310: - **WHEN** the invocation completes\n311: - **THEN** the CLI SHALL:\n312:   - Print the response in a formatted manner\n313: \n314: #### Scenario 8.2: Agent returns error response\n315: - **GIVEN** the agent endpoint returns an error response (4xx or 5xx)\n316: - **WHEN** the invocation completes\n317: - **THEN** the CLI SHALL:\n318:   - Display the error message\n319:   - Display response details\n320: \n321: #### Scenario 8.3: Network timeout\n322: - **GIVEN** the invocation request times out\n323: - **WHEN** the timeout period elapses\n324: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n325:   - Raise a timeout exception\n326:   - Handle exception via `_handle_error`\n327: \n328: ---\n329: \n330: ## REQ-009: Error handling for invoke\n331: \n332: ### Requirement: Consistent error handling\n333: \n334: System SHALL use consistent error handling patterns for all exceptions.\n335: \n336: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n337: - Catches runtime exceptions\n338: - Displays error messages in red\n339: - Shows tracebacks in verbose mode\n340: - Exits with code 1 on errors\n341: \n342: **Scenarios:**\n343: \n344: #### Scenario 9.1: Runtime exception\n345: - **GIVEN** `InvokeRuntime.invoke` raises a `RuntimeError`\n346: - **WHEN** the exception is caught by the CLI\n347: - **THEN** `_handle_error` SHALL:\n348:   - Print \"Error invoke: {error_message}\" in red\n349:   - If `verbose` is `True`, print the full traceback\n350:   - Exit with code `1` via `typer.Exit(1)`\n351: \n352: #### Scenario 9.2: HTTP connection error\n353: - **GIVEN** there is a network connectivity issue\n354: - **WHEN** the invocation attempt fails\n355: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n356:   - Catch the connection error\n357:   - Surface it via `_handle_error`\n358: \n359: #### Scenario 9.3: Subcommand verbose logging\n360: - **GIVEN** the user uses the local `--verbose` flag on the `invoke` command\n361: - **WHEN** an error occurs\n362: - **THEN** the traceback SHALL be:\n363:   - Printed even if the global `-v` was not passed\n364: \n365: ---\n366: \n367: ## REQ-010: Status command initialization\n368: \n369: ### Requirement: Status command registration and default options\n370: \n371: System SHALL provide a `status` command that displays the current state of a deployed agent.\n372: \n373: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n374: - Command name: `status`\n375: - Supports workspace path specification\n376: - Supports provider selection (agentcube/k8s)\n377: - Provides verbose mode for detailed logging\n378: - Displays status in formatted table\n379: \n380: **Scenarios:**\n381: \n382: #### Scenario 10.1: Command registration and default options\n383: - **GIVEN** the AgentCube CLI Typer application is initialized\n384: - **WHEN** the user runs `kubectl-agentcube status` without options\n385: - **THEN** the system SHALL use these defaults:\n386:   - `workspace`: `\".\"` (current directory)\n387:   - `provider`: `\"agentcube\"`\n388:   - `verbose`: `False`\n389: \n390: #### Scenario 10.2: Custom workspace and provider\n391: - **GIVEN** the user specifies custom options\n392: - **WHEN** parsing `status -f /path/to/workspace --provider k8s`\n393: - **THEN** the system SHALL use:\n394:   - `workspace`: `\"/path/to/workspace\"`\n395:   - `provider`: `\"k8s\"`\n396:   - `verbose`: `False`\n397: \n398: ---\n399: \n400: ## REQ-011: Status display formatting\n401: \n402: ### Requirement: Rich table formatting\n403: \n404: System SHALL display agent status in a Rich `Table` with clear, readable formatting.\n405: \n406: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n407: - Displays status in Rich table\n408: - Shows key information fields\n409: - Handles missing fields gracefully\n410: - Provides clear status indication\n411: \n412: **Scenarios:**\n413: \n414: #### Scenario 11.1: Successful status retrieval\n415: - **GIVEN** the agent is successfully deployed and status is available\n416: - **WHEN** `status` runs and retrieves status information\n417: - **THEN** the CLI SHALL display:\n418:   - A Rich `Table` containing:\n419:     - Field names in the first column\n420:     - Field values in the second column\n421:     - Key information: agent name, namespace, status, endpoint, deployment details\n422: \n423: #### Scenario 11.2: Status table fields\n424: - **GIVEN** the agent status is retrieved\n425: - **WHEN** the Rich table is rendered\n426: - **THEN** it SHALL include these fields when available:\n427:   - Agent Name\n428:   - Namespace\n429:   - Status (e.g., \"running\", \"ready\", \"error\", \"not_published\")\n430:   - Agent Endpoint\n431:   - Session ID (if applicable)\n432:   - Deployment Type (AgentRuntime or Deployment/Service)\n433:   - Image URL\n434:   - Version\n435: \n436: #### Scenario 11.3: Status not published\n437: - **GIVEN** the agent metadata has no `agent_id` field\n438: - **WHEN** `status` is called and returns `status == \"not_published\"`\n439: - **THEN** the CLI SHALL:\n440:   - Print a message indicating the agent is not published\n441:   - Provide guidance to run `publish` command first\n442:   - Exit with code `1`\n443: \n444: ---\n445: \n446: ## REQ-012: Status for AgentCube provider\n447: \n448: ### Requirement: AgentRuntime CR status retrieval\n449: \n450: System SHALL retrieve and display status for agents deployed via the AgentCube provider.\n451: \n452: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n453: - Retrieves status from AgentRuntime CR\n454: - Handles CR with status field\n455: - Handles CR without status field\n456: - Handles CR not found\n457: \n458: **Scenarios:**\n459: \n460: #### Scenario 12.1: AgentRuntime CR with status\n461: - **GIVEN** `provider` is `\"agentcube\"`\n462: - **WHEN** the AgentRuntime CR exists with status\n463: - **THEN** `StatusRuntime._get_cr_k8s_status` SHALL:\n464:   - Read status from `cr_object[\"status\"]` when present\n465:   - Extract `status` and `agentEndpoint` from the CR status\n466: \n467: #### Scenario 12.2: AgentRuntime CR created but no status\n468: - **GIVEN** `provider` is `\"agentcube\"`\n469: - **WHEN** the AgentRuntime CR exists but has no status field\n470: - **THEN** `StatusRuntime._get_cr_k8s_status` SHALL:\n471:   - Return status `\"created_no_status\"`\n472: \n473: #### Scenario 12.3: AgentRuntime CR not found\n474: - **GIVEN** `provider` is `\"agentcube\"`\n475: - **WHEN** the AgentRuntime CR does not exist\n476: - **THEN** `StatusRuntime._get_cr_k8s_status` SHALL:\n477:   - Return status `\"not_found_in_k8s\"`\n478: \n479: #### Scenario 12.4: AgentRuntime CR error status\n480: - **GIVEN** the AgentRuntime CR status indicates an error condition\n481: - **WHEN** status is retrieved\n482: - **THEN** the CLI SHALL:\n483:   - Display error details\n484:   - Exit with code `1`\n485: \n486: ---\n487: \n488: ## REQ-013: Status for Kubernetes provider\n489: \n490: ### Requirement: K8s Deployment/Service status retrieval\n491: \n492: System SHALL retrieve and display status for agents deployed via the standard Kubernetes provider.\n493: \n494: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n495: - Queries both Deployment and Service status\n496: - Displays deployment ready replicas\n497: - Displays service node port and URL\n498: - Handles resources not found\n499: \n500: **Scenarios:**\n501: \n502: #### Scenario 13.1: K8s deployment and service status\n503: - **GIVEN** `provider` is `\"k8s\"`\n504: - **WHEN** the agent is deployed with Deployment and Service\n505: - **THEN** `StatusRuntime._get_k8s_status` SHALL:\n506:   - Query both Deployment and Service status\n507:   - Include:\n508:     - Deployment ready replicas\n509:     - Service node port\n510:     - Service URL\n511:     - Pod status summary\n512: \n513: #### Scenario 13.2: K8s deployment not ready\n514: - **GIVEN** the Deployment exists but replicas are not ready\n515: - **WHEN** status is retrieved\n516: - **THEN** the status SHALL indicate:\n517:   - `\"not_ready\"` with details about current vs. desired replicas\n518: \n519: #### Scenario 13.3: K8s resources not found\n520: - **GIVEN** `provider` is `\"k8s\"`\n521: - **WHEN** neither Deployment nor Service exists\n522: - **THEN** the status SHALL indicate:\n523:   - `\"not_found_in_k8s\"`\n524: \n525: ---\n526: \n527: ## REQ-014: Status exit codes\n528: \n529: ### Requirement: Appropriate exit codes\n530: \n531: System SHALL use appropriate exit codes to indicate the result of status checks.\n532: \n533: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n534: - Exit code 0 for success/ready\n535: - Exit code 1 for failure/not-ready/not-published\n536: \n537: **Scenarios:**\n538: \n539: #### Scenario 14.1: Successful status (agent running)\n540: - **GIVEN** the agent status indicates it is running or ready\n541: - **WHEN** `status` completes\n542: - **THEN** the CLI SHALL exit with:\n543:   - code `0`\n544: \n545: #### Scenario 14.2: Agent not published\n546: - **GIVEN** the agent has no `agent_id` in metadata\n547: - **WHEN** `status` completes\n548: - **THEN** the CLI SHALL exit with:\n549:   - code `1`\n550: \n551: #### Scenario 14.3: Agent in error state\n552: - **GIVEN** the agent status indicates an error condition\n553: - **WHEN** `status` completes\n554: - **THEN** the CLI SHALL exit with:\n555:   - code `1`\n556: \n557: #### Scenario 14.4: Agent not found in Kubernetes\n558: - **GIVEN** the agent was previously published but the CR or Deployment no longer exists\n559: - **WHEN** `status` completes\n560: - **THEN** the CLI SHALL exit with:\n561:   - code `1`\n562: \n563: ---\n564: \n565: ## REQ-015: Workspace path resolution for status\n566: \n567: ### Requirement: Path resolution for status\n568: \n569: System SHALL resolve the workspace path for status checks.\n570: \n571: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n572: - Uses current directory as default\n573: - Resolves custom paths correctly\n574: - Validates path existence\n575: \n576: **Scenarios:**\n577: \n578: #### Scenario 15.1: Default workspace\n579: - **GIVEN** the user runs `status` without `-f` option\n580: - **WHEN** the workspace path is resolved\n581: - **THEN** it SHALL use:\n582:   - The current working directory `\".\"`\n583: \n584: #### Scenario 15.2: Custom workspace path\n585: - **GIVEN** the user runs `status -f /path/to/agent`\n586: - **WHEN** the workspace path is resolved\n587: - **THEN** it SHALL use:\n588:   - `/path/to/agent`\n589: \n590: #### Scenario 15.3: Missing workspace\n591: - **GIVEN** the specified workspace path does not exist\n592: - **WHEN** `status` is called\n593: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n594:   - Raise a `ValueError` indicating the directory does not exist\n595: \n596: ---\n597: \n598: ## REQ-016: Verbose logging for status\n599: \n600: ### Requirement: Detailed logging support\n601: \n602: System SHALL provide detailed logging when verbose mode is enabled.\n603: \n604: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n605: - Logs Kubernetes API calls\n606: - Logs resource retrieval\n607: - Logs status parsing\n608: - Logs warnings and additional information\n609: \n610: **Scenarios:**\n611: \n612: #### Scenario 16.1: Verbose status output\n613: - **GIVEN** the user runs `status --verbose`\n614: - **WHEN** status is retrieved\n615: - **THEN** the system SHALL log:\n616:   - Additional details about Kubernetes API calls\n617:   - CR or resource retrieval\n618:   - Status parsing\n619:   - Any warnings or additional information\n620: \n621: ---\n622: \n623: ## REQ-017: Error handling for status\n624: \n625: ### Requirement: Consistent error handling\n626: \n627: System SHALL use consistent error handling patterns for all exceptions.\n628: \n629: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n630: - Catches runtime exceptions\n631: - Displays error messages in red\n632: - Shows tracebacks in verbose mode\n633: - Exits with code 1 on errors\n634: \n635: **Scenarios:**\n636: \n637: #### Scenario 17.1: Status retrieval exception\n638: - **GIVEN** `StatusRuntime.get_status` raises a `RuntimeError`\n639: - **WHEN** the exception is caught by the CLI\n640: - **THEN** `_handle_error` SHALL:\n641:   - Print \"Error status: {error_message}\" in red\n642:   - If `verbose` is `True`, print the full traceback\n643:   - Exit with code `1` via `typer.Exit(1)`\n644: \n645: #### Scenario 17.2: Kubernetes connection error\n646: - **GIVEN** there is an issue connecting to the Kubernetes API\n647: - **WHEN** `status` attempts to query the cluster\n648: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n649:   - Catch the connection error\n650:   - Surface it via `_handle_error`\n651: \n652: #### Scenario 17.3: Metadata validation error\n653: - **GIVEN** the metadata file exists but contains invalid data\n654: - **WHEN** `status` attempts to load metadata\n655: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n656:   - Catch the validation error\n657:   - Surface it via `_handle_error`\n658: \n659: ---\n660: \n661: ## REQ-018: Metadata file loading\n662: \n663: ### Requirement: Metadata loading with fallback\n664: \n665: System SHALL load agent metadata from the workspace with appropriate fallback behavior.\n666: \n667: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n668: - Loads from agent_metadata.yaml first\n669: - Falls back to agent.yaml\n670: - Falls back to metadata.yaml\n671: - Raises error if none found\n672: \n673: **Scenarios:**\n674: \n675: #### Scenario 18.1: Primary metadata file exists\n676: - **GIVEN** `agent_metadata.yaml` exists in the workspace\n677: - **WHEN** metadata is loaded for `invoke` or `status`\n678: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n679:   - Load from `agent_metadata.yaml`\n680: \n681: #### Scenario 18.2: Primary missing, first fallback\n682: - **GIVEN** `agent_metadata.yaml` does not exist\n683: - **WHEN** `agent.yaml` does exist\n684: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n685:   - Load from `agent.yaml`\n686: \n687: #### Scenario 18.3: Primary and first fallback missing\n688: - **GIVEN** neither `agent_metadata.yaml` nor `agent.yaml` exists\n689: - **WHEN** `metadata.yaml` does exist\n690: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n691:   - Load from `metadata.yaml`\n692: \n693: #### Scenario 18.4: No metadata file found\n694: - **GIVEN** no metadata file exists in the workspace\n695: - **WHEN** metadata is loaded\n696: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n697:   - Raise an error indicating no metadata file was found\n698: \n699: ---\n700: \n701: ## REQ-019: Global verbose logging propagation\n702: \n703: ### Requirement: Verbose flag propagation\n704: \n705: System SHALL correctly propagate verbose logging settings from the root callback to subcommands.\n706: \n707: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n708: - Global verbose enables logging for all subcommands\n709: - Subcommand verbose enables logging for that subcommand\n710: - Combination of both works correctly\n711: \n712: **Scenarios:**\n713: \n714: #### Scenario 19.1: Global verbose with subcommand verbose\n715: - **GIVEN** the user passes both global `-v` and local `--verbose` on `invoke` or `status`\n716: - **WHEN** the command runs\n717: - **THEN** verbose logging SHALL be:\n718:   - Enabled\n719: \n720: #### Scenario 19.2: Subcommand verbose without global verbose\n721: - **GIVEN** the user passes only `invoke --verbose` without global `-v`\n722: - **WHEN** the command runs\n723: - **THEN** verbose logging SHALL be:\n724:   - Enabled for that subcommand\n725: \n726: #### Scenario 19.3: Global verbose without subcommand verbose\n727: - **GIVEN** the user passes only global `-v` without subcommand `--verbose`\n728: - **WHEN** `invoke` or `status` runs\n729: - **THEN** verbose logging SHALL be:\n730:   - Enabled\n731: \n732: ---\n733: \n734: ## REQ-020: Rich output formatting\n735: \n736: ### Requirement: Consistent Rich library usage\n737: \n738: System SHALL use Rich library for consistent, readable command output.\n739: \n740: **Acceptance Criteria:**\n741: - Uses Rich table for status\n742: - Uses Rich console for errors\n743: - Uses Rich progress spinner for long operations\n744: \n745: **Scenarios:**\n746: \n747: #### Scenario 20.1: Rich table for status\n748: - **GIVEN** status information is available\n749: - **WHEN** displaying status\n750: - **THEN** the output SHALL be:\n751:   - Formatted as a Rich table with proper styling\n752: \n753: #### Scenario 20.2: Rich console for errors\n754: - **GIVEN** an error occurs\n755: - **WHEN** the error is displayed\n756: - **THEN** error messages SHALL use:\n757:   - Rich console for red-colored output\n758: \n759: #### Scenario 20.3: Rich progress spinner\n760: - **GIVEN** a long-running operation\n761: - **WHEN** the operation is in progress\n762: - **THEN** the system SHALL display:\n763:   - A Rich Progress spinner\n764: \n765: ---\n766: \n767: ## Integration Scenarios\n768: \n769: ### INT-001: Full workflow - pack, build, publish, invoke\n770: \n771: #### Scenario INT-1.1: Complete lifecycle\n772: - **GIVEN** a valid agent workspace\n773: - **WHEN** the user runs:\n774:   1. `pack` - successfully packages the workspace\n775:   2. `build` - successfully builds the image\n776:   3. `publish --provider agentcube` - successfully deploys to Kubernetes\n777:   4. `invoke --payload '{\"query\": \"test\"}'` - sends a payload\n778: - **THEN** each command SHALL:\n779:   - Complete successfully\n780:   - `invoke` SHALL receive a response from the deployed agent\n781: \n782: #### Scenario INT-1.2: Invoke after local build publish\n783: - **GIVEN** an agent built in local mode\n784: - **WHEN** published with `--image-url` and `--provider k8s`\n785: - **THEN** `invoke --provider k8s` SHALL:\n786:   - Successfully send requests to the NodePort service\n787: \n788: ### INT-002: Status checks during deployment lifecycle\n789: \n790: #### Scenario INT-2.1: Status before publish\n791: - **GIVEN** an agent has been packed but not published\n792: - **WHEN** `status` is run\n793: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n794:   - Indicate the agent is not published\n795:   - Exit with code `1`\n796: \n797: #### Scenario INT-2.2: Status during deployment rollout\n798: - **GIVEN** an agent has been published and is in the process of becoming ready\n799: - **WHEN** `status` is run\n800: - **THEN** the system SHALL show:\n801:   - The current deployment state (e.g., \"not_ready\")\n802: \n803: #### Scenario INT-2.3: Status after agent is ready\n804: - **GIVEN** an agent deployment has completed successfully\n805: - **WHEN** `status` is run\n806: - **THEN** the system SHALL show:\n807:   - Status \"ready\" or \"running\" with full endpoint information\n808: \n809: ### INT-003: Session management across invokes\n810: \n811: #### Scenario INT-3.1: Reuse session ID from metadata\n812: - **GIVEN** the first `invoke` establishes a session\n813: - **WHEN** it saves `session_id` to metadata\n814: - **THEN** subsequent `invoke` commands SHALL:\n815:   - Use the existing `session_id` from metadata\n816: \n817: #### Scenario INT-3.2: Session ID in headers\n818: - **GIVEN** metadata contains `session_id: \"existing-session\"`\n819: - **WHEN** `invoke` is called with `--header 'X-Agentcube-Session-Id: new-session'`\n820: - **THEN** the custom header SHALL:\n821:   - Override the metadata session ID for that specific request\n822: \n823: ---\n824: \n825: ## Edge Cases and Error Conditions\n826: \n827: ### EDGE-001: Malformed metadata\n828: \n829: #### Scenario EDGE-1.1: Missing required fields\n830: - **GIVEN** the metadata file exists but lacks required fields\n831: - **WHEN** `invoke` or `status` attempts to load metadata\n832: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n833:   - Raise a validation error indicating which fields are missing\n834: \n835: #### Scenario EDGE-1.2: Invalid data types in metadata\n836: - **GIVEN** the metadata file contains fields with invalid data types\n837: - **WHEN** Pydantic validation runs\n838: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n839:   - Raise a validation error with details about the type mismatch\n840: \n841: ### EDGE-002: Concurrent invocations\n842: \n843: #### Scenario EDGE-2.1: Multiple invocations in parallel\n844: - **GIVEN** an agent is deployed and ready\n845: - **WHEN** multiple `invoke` commands are run simultaneously\n846: - **THEN** each invocation SHALL:\n847:   - Receive its own response\n848:   - Have session headers correctly applied to each request\n849: \n850: ### EDGE-003: Large payloads\n851: \n852: #### Scenario EDGE-3.1: Large JSON payload\n853: - **GIVEN** the user provides a large JSON payload (e.g., 1MB)\n854: - **WHEN** `invoke --payload` is called with the large payload\n855: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n856:   - Successfully parse and send the payload to the agent endpoint\n857: \n858: #### Scenario EDGE-3.2: Extremely large payload rejection\n859: - **GIVEN** the user provides an extremely large JSON payload exceeding system limits\n860: - **WHEN** `invoke --payload` is called\n861: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n862:   - Reject the payload with an appropriate error message\n863: \n864: ---\n865: \n866: ## Provider-specific Edge Cases\n867: \n868: ### EDGE-004: AgentCube provider edge cases\n869: \n870: #### Scenario EDGE-4.1: Missing router_url\n871: - **GIVEN** `provider` is `\"agentcube\"`\n872: - **WHEN** metadata lacks `router_url`\n873: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n874:   - Raise an error indicating `router_url` is required for AgentCube provider\n875: \n876: #### Scenario EDGE-4.2: AgentRuntime CR with missing status field\n877: - **GIVEN** the AgentRuntime CR exists\n878: - **WHEN** it has no status field in its spec\n879: - **THEN** `status` SHALL:\n880:   - Handle gracefully and return appropriate status\n881: \n882: ### EDGE-005: Kubernetes provider edge cases\n883: \n884: #### Scenario EDGE-5.1: NodePort outside valid range\n885: - **GIVEN** a K8s deployment was created with an invalid NodePort\n886: - **WHEN** `invoke --provider k8s` attempts to connect\n887: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n888:   - Handle connection errors appropriately\n889: \n890: #### Scenario EDGE-5.2: Service with no endpoints\n891: - **GIVEN** the K8s Service exists\n892: - **WHEN** it has no ready endpoints\n893: - **THEN** `invoke --provider k8s` SHALL:\n894:   - Handle connection errors\n895:   - Provide informative messages\n896: \n897: ---\n898: \n899: ## Technical Constraints\n900: \n901: ### Requirement: Language and dependencies\n902: \n903: System SHALL use Python 3.10+ and the following dependencies:\n904: \n905: **Dependencies:**\n906: - `typer[all]>=0.9.0` for CLI framework\n907: - `pydantic>=2.0.0` for data validation\n908: - `pyyaml>=6.0` for YAML parsing\n909: - `httpx>=0.24.0` for HTTP client\n910: - `rich>=13.0.0` for formatted console output\n911: - `kubernetes>=28.0.0` for Kubernetes API client (optional)\n912: \n913: ### Requirement: File locations\n914: \n915: - CLI command definition: `agentcube/cli/main.py`\n916: - InvokeRuntime implementation: `agentcube/runtime/invoke_runtime.py`\n917: - StatusRuntime implementation: `agentcube/runtime/status_runtime.py`\n918: - MetadataService implementation: `agentcube/services/metadata_service.py`\n919: - Metadata model: `agentcube/services/metadata_service.py`\n920: - Metadata filename: `agent_metadata.yaml`\n921: \n922: ### Requirement: Exit codes\n923: \n924: System SHALL return appropriate exit codes:\n925: - Exit code 0 for successful operations\n926: - Exit code 1 for failures\n927: - Exit code 130 for SIGINT (Ctrl+C) interruption\n928: \n929: ---\n930: \n931: ## Testing Requirements\n932: \n933: ### Unit Test Scenarios\n934: \n935: #### Scenario UT-1.1: Test payload validation\n936: - **GIVEN** a test suite for payload validation\n937: - **WHEN** tests run\n938: - **THEN** tests SHALL cover:\n939:   - Valid JSON payload parsing\n940:   - Invalid JSON payload rejection\n941:   - Empty payload default handling\n942:   - Complex nested payload parsing\n943: \n944: #### Scenario UT-1.2: Test header validation\n945: - **GIVEN** a test suite for header validation\n946: - **WHEN** tests run\n947: - **THEN** tests SHALL cover:\n948:   - Valid header format parsing\n949:   - Invalid header format rejection\n950:   - Multiple headers handling\n951:   - Headers with colons in values\n952:   - Empty header values\n953: \n954: #### Scenario UT-1.3: Test session header management\n955: - **GIVEN** a test suite for session header management\n956: - **WHEN** tests run\n957: - **THEN** tests SHALL cover:\n958:   - Session header injection when session_id exists\n959:   - No session header when session_id is missing\n960:   - Custom header override of session_id\n961: \n962: #### Scenario UT-1.4: Test provider routing\n963: - **GIVEN** a test suite for provider routing\n964: - **WHEN** tests run\n965: - **THEN** tests SHALL cover:\n966:   - AgentCube provider URL rewriting\n967:   - K8s provider direct routing\n968:   - Router URL usage for AgentCube provider\n969: \n970: #### Scenario UT-1.5: Test status retrieval\n971: - **GIVEN** a test suite for status retrieval\n972: - **WHEN** tests run\n973: - **THEN** tests SHALL cover:\n974:   - AgentRuntime CR status retrieval\n975:   - K8s Deployment/Service status retrieval\n976:   - CR not found handling\n977:   - CR without status handling\n978:   - Resources not found handling\n979: \n980: ### Integration Test Scenarios\n981: \n982: #### Scenario IT-1.1: End-to-end invoke for AgentCube provider\n983: - **GIVEN** a deployed agent with AgentRuntime CR\n984: - **WHEN** user runs `kubectl-agentcube invoke --payload '{\"test\": \"data\"}'`\n985: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n986:   - Load metadata from workspace\n987:   - Construct correct invocation URL\n988:   - Send payload with proper headers\n989:   - Receive and display response\n990: \n991: #### Scenario IT-1.2: End-to-end invoke for K8s provider\n992: - **GIVEN** a deployed agent with Deployment/Service\n993: - **WHEN** user runs `kubectl-agentcube invoke --provider k8s --payload '{\"test\": \"data\"}'`\n994: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n995:   - Load metadata from workspace\n996:   - Use service URL for invocation\n997:   - Send payload with proper headers\n998:   - Receive and display response\n999: \n1000: #### Scenario IT-1.3: End-to-end status for AgentCube provider\n1001: - **GIVEN** a deployed agent with AgentRuntime CR\n1002: - **WHEN** user runs `kubectl-agentcube status`\n1003: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n1004:   - Load metadata from workspace\n1005:   - Query AgentRuntime CR\n1006:   - Display status in Rich table\n1007:   - Exit with appropriate code\n1008: \n1009: #### Scenario IT-1.4: End-to-end status for K8s provider\n1010: - **GIVEN** a deployed agent with Deployment/Service\n1011: - **WHEN** user runs `kubectl-agentcube status --provider k8s`\n1012: - **THEN** the system SHALL:\n1013:   - Load metadata from workspace\n1014:   - Query Deployment and Service\n1015:   - Display status in Rich table\n1016:   - Exit with appropriate code\n1017: \n1018: ### Error Handling Test Scenarios\n1019: \n1020: #### Scenario ET-1.1: Test error propagation for invoke\n1021: - **GIVEN** various error conditions for invoke\n1022: - **WHEN** errors occur during invocation\n1023: - **THEN** tests SHALL verify:\n1024:   - Invalid JSON payload displays error and exits with code 1\n1025:   - Invalid header format displays error and exits with code 1\n1026:   - Agent not published displays error and exits with code 1\n1027:   - Network errors are caught and surfaced\n1028:   - CLI displays error message in red\n1029:   - CLI shows traceback in verbose mode\n1030: \n1031: #### Scenario ET-1.2: Test error propagation for status\n1032: - **GIVEN** various error conditions for status\n1033: - **WHEN** errors occur during status check\n1034: - **THEN** tests SHALL verify:\n1035:   - Agent not published displays guidance and exits with code 1\n1036:   - Kubernetes connection errors are caught and surfaced\n1037:   - Metadata validation errors are caught and surfaced\n1038:   - CLI displays error message in red\n1039:   - CLI shows traceback in verbose mode\n1040: \n1041: ---\n1042: \n1043: ## Acceptance Criteria\n1044: \n1045: ### Functional Acceptance Criteria - Invoke Command\n1046: \n1047: - [ ] Invoke command accepts all documented options with correct types and defaults\n1048: - [ ] Invalid JSON payloads are rejected with clear error messages\n1049: - [ ] Invalid header formats are rejected with clear error messages\n1050: - [ ] Session headers are automatically added when session_id exists in metadata\n1051: - [ ] Workspace paths are resolved correctly (relative and absolute)\n1052: - [ ] AgentCube provider routes to AgentRuntime invocation endpoint\n1053: - [ ] K8s provider routes directly to service endpoint\n1054: - [ ] Prerequisites are validated before invocation attempts\n1055: - [ ] Successful responses are displayed in a readable format\n1056: - [ ] Error responses and timeouts are handled gracefully\n1057: - [ ] Verbose mode provides detailed logging and traces\n1058: - [ ] Exit code 0 on success, 1 on failure\n1059: \n1060: ### Functional Acceptance Criteria - Status Command\n1061: \n1062: - [ ] Status command accepts all documented options with correct types and defaults\n1063: - [ ] Status is displayed in a Rich table with clear formatting\n1064: - [ ] \"Not published\" state is detected and reported with guidance\n1065: - [ ] AgentRuntime CR status is correctly retrieved and parsed\n1066: - [ ] K8s Deployment/Service status is correctly retrieved and parsed\n1067: - [ ] Exit code 0 on success/ready, 1 on failure/not-ready/not-published\n1068: - [ ] Workspace paths are resolved correctly\n1069: - [ ] Verbose mode provides additional debugging information\n1070: - [ ] Errors are caught and surfaced via _handle_error\n1071: \n1072: ### Non-Functional Acceptance Criteria\n1073: \n1074: - [ ] Invoke command completes within reasonable time for typical payloads\n1075: - [ ] Status command completes within reasonable time for typical queries\n1076: - [ ] Memory usage remains reasonable for large payloads\n1077: - [ ] Path traversal protection prevents unauthorized access\n1078: - [ ] Sensitive information in headers is handled securely\n1079: - [ ] Error messages are clear and actionable\n1080: - [ ] Unit tests cover all major code paths\n1081: - [ ] Integration tests cover end-to-end scenarios\n1082: - [ ] Error handling tests verify proper error propagation and display\n1083: \n1084: ---\n1085: \n1086: ## Implementation Notes\n1087: \n1088: ### Key Components\n1089: \n1090: 1. **InvokeRuntime** (`agentcube/runtime/invoke_runtime.py`)\n1091:    - Main runtime class implementing invoke logic\n1092:    - Handles payload validation, header processing, and HTTP requests\n1093:    - Routes to appropriate provider endpoints\n1094: \n1095: 2. **StatusRuntime** (`agentcube/runtime/status_runtime.py`)\n1096:    - Main runtime class implementing status logic\n1097:    - Handles AgentRuntime CR and K8s resource queries\n1098:    - Formats status output for display\n1099: \n1100: 3. **MetadataService** (`agentcube/services/metadata_service.py`)\n1101:    - Handles metadata loading and saving\n1102:    - Provides validation methods for metadata fields\n1103: \n1104: 4. **AgentMetadata** (`agentcube/services/metadata_service.py`)\n1105:    - Pydantic model for metadata validation\n1106:    - Contains all agent configuration fields\n1107: \n1108: 5. **Typer CLI framework**\n1109:    - Provides command-line interface definition\n1110:    - Handles option parsing and validation\n1111: \n1112: 6. **Rich library**\n1113:    - Provides formatted console output\n1114:    - Supports tables, progress spinners, and colored text\n1115: \n1116: ### Key Algorithms\n1117: \n1118: #### Invoke Algorithm\n1119: 1. Load metadata from workspace\n1120: 2. Validate agent is published (has agent_id)\n1121: 3. Parse JSON payload (validate syntax)\n1122: 4. Parse custom headers (validate format)\n1123: 5. Determine provider (agentcube or k8s)\n1124: 6. Construct invocation URL based on provider\n1125: 7. Add session header if session_id exists in metadata\n1126: 8. Send HTTP POST request with payload and headers\n1127: 9. Handle response or error\n1128: 10. Display result or error message\n1129: \n1130: #### Status Algorithm\n1131: 1. Load metadata from workspace\n1132: 2. Check if agent is published (has agent_id)\n1133: 3. Determine provider (agentcube or k8s)\n1134: 4. For agentcube provider:\n1135:    - Query AgentRuntime CR\n1136:    - Extract status and endpoint from CR\n1137: 5. For k8s provider:\n1138:    - Query Deployment and Service\n1139:    - Extract deployment and service status\n1140: 6. Format status information in Rich table\n1141: 7. Display table to user\n1142: 8. Exit with appropriate code\n1143: \n1144: #### Header Parsing Algorithm\n1145: 1. For each header string in header_list:\n1146:    - Split at first `:` to get key and value\n1147:    - Validate split produced exactly 2 parts\n1148:    - If not, raise error with format message\n1149: 2. Return dictionary of key-value pairs\n1150: \n1151: #### Session Header Injection Algorithm\n1152: 1. Check if metadata.session_id exists and is truthy\n1153: 2. If yes, add header `X-Agentcube-Session-Id: {session_id}`\n1154: 3. Check if custom headers already contain this header\n1155: 4. If custom headers exist, they take precedence\n1156: 5. Return final headers dictionary\n1157: \n1158: ---\n1159: \n1160: ## Related Requirements\n1161: \n1162: - **AR-020:** CLI pack command (required before invoke/status)\n1163: - **AR-021:** CLI build command (required before invoke/status)\n1164: - **AR-022:** CLI publish command (required before invoke/status)\n1165: - **AR-024:** CLI additional commands (future work)\n1166: - **cli-toolkit/spec.md:** Base CLI specifications\n1167: - **deployment/client-go.md:** Kubernetes client for AgentRuntime CR\n1168: - **python-sdk/spec.md:** SDK requirements and HTTP contracts\n\n(End of file - total 1168 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Delta Specification: AR-023 — CLI invoke/status Commands\n\n## Module: `cmd/cli`\n\n## Language: Python\n\n## Size: M\n\n## Delta Overview\n\nAdd the `invoke` and `status` commands to the AgentCube CLI for sending payloads to deployed agents and checking their deployment status, supporting both AgentCube (AgentRuntime CR) and standard Kubernetes (Deployment/Service) providers.\n\n---\n\n## REQ-001: Invoke command initialization\n\n### Requirement: Invoke command registration and default options\n\nSystem SHALL provide an `invoke` command that sends JSON payloads to deployed agent endpoints with configurable options.\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775870803272,"end":1775870803281}}}}
