{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1775870815857,"sessionID":"ses_285daca2dffetuopp54L7bgIWw","part":{"id":"prt_d7a262e6e001QvQOX3Y6wvvkUf","messageID":"msg_d7a262a0e001yyYu5vpBs7ik2Z","sessionID":"ses_285daca2dffetuopp54L7bgIWw","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775870920052,"sessionID":"ses_285daca2dffetuopp54L7bgIWw","part":{"id":"prt_d7a27c513001UvLxaVlR5zs3s6","messageID":"msg_d7a262a0e001yyYu5vpBs7ik2Z","sessionID":"ses_285daca2dffetuopp54L7bgIWw","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_tool-dc7db4fcc56f44fa8607cf61651249c1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"content":"# Delta Specification: AR-024 — DockerService 封装\n\n## Module: `cmd/cli`\n\n## Language: Python\n\n## Size: M\n\n## Delta Overview\n\nEnhance and formalize the `DockerService` class to provide a robust, well-encapsulated interface for Docker operations including image building, pushing, tagging, and management. This specification defines the complete behavior, error handling, and testing requirements for the Docker service layer used by the AgentCube CLI's build and publish workflows.\n\n---\n\n## REQ-001: DockerService initialization and configuration\n\n### Requirement: Service initialization with verbose logging\n\nSystem SHALL provide a `DockerService` class that initializes with optional verbose logging and configures the Docker client properly.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Constructor accepts optional verbose boolean parameter\n- Stores verbose flag for use in logging operations\n- Initializes Docker client using `docker.from_env()`\n- Handles Docker client initialization failures gracefully\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n#### Scenario 1.1: Initialize with verbose logging enabled\n- **GIVEN** a developer creates a `DockerService` instance with `verbose=True`\n- **WHEN** the service initializes\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Store the verbose flag as an instance variable\n  - Initialize the Docker client using `docker.from_env()`\n  - Log initialization message if verbose is enabled\n\n#### Scenario 1.2: Initialize with verbose logging disabled\n- **GIVEN** a developer creates a `DockerService` instance with `verbose=False` or no verbose parameter\n- **WHEN** the service initializes\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Store `verbose=False` as an instance variable\n  - Initialize the Docker client using `docker.from_env()`\n  - NOT log initialization message\n\n#### Scenario 1.3: Docker client initialization failure\n- **GIVEN** Docker daemon is not running or not installed\n- **WHEN** `DockerService.__init__()` attempts to initialize the client\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Raise an appropriate exception (e.g., `RuntimeError` or `docker.errors.DockerException`)\n  - Include a descriptive message about Docker availability\n\n---\n\n## REQ-002: Docker availability checking\n\n### Requirement: Check Docker daemon availability\n\nSystem SHALL provide a method to check if Docker daemon is available and running.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Method returns boolean indicating Docker availability\n- Logs availability check result when verbose is enabled\n- Handles connection failures gracefully\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n#### Scenario 2.1: Docker daemon is available\n- **GIVEN** Docker daemon is running and accessible\n- **WHEN** `check_docker_available()` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Attempt to connect to Docker daemon\n  - Return `True` if connection succeeds\n  - Log \"Docker is available\" if verbose is enabled\n\n#### Scenario 2.2: Docker daemon is not available\n- **GIVEN** Docker daemon is not running or not installed\n- **WHEN** `check_docker_available()` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Attempt to connect to Docker daemon\n  - Return `False` if connection fails\n  - Log a warning message if verbose is enabled\n  - NOT raise an exception (return gracefully)\n\n#### Scenario 2.3: Docker client not initialized\n- **GIVEN** the DockerService instance was not properly initialized\n- **WHEN** `check_docker_available()` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Return `False`\n  - Log appropriate error message if verbose is enabled\n\n---\n\n## REQ-003: Docker image building\n\n### Requirement: Build Docker images from Dockerfiles\n\nSystem SHALL provide a method to build Docker images with configurable options.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Accepts dockerfile path, context path, image name, and optional tag\n- Supports build arguments for proxy configuration\n- Streams build logs in real-time\n- Returns detailed build result information\n- Handles build failures with descriptive errors\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n#### Scenario 3.1: Build image with default tag\n- **GIVEN** a valid Dockerfile at `/path/to/Dockerfile`\n- **AND** a build context directory at `/path/to/context`\n- **WHEN** `build_image(dockerfile_path=\"/path/to/Dockerfile\", context_path=\"/path/to/context\", image_name=\"myimage\")` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Build the image with tag `\"latest\"` by default\n  - Return a dict containing:\n    - `image_name`: `\"myimage:latest\"`\n    - `image_id`: the SHA256 hash of the built image\n    - `image_size`: human-readable size string\n    - `build_time`: ISO 8601 timestamp\n\n#### Scenario 3.2: Build image with custom tag\n- **GIVEN** a valid Dockerfile and build context\n- **WHEN** `build_image(..., tag=\"v1.0.0\")` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Build the image with tag `\"v1.0.0\"`\n  - Return result with `image_name: \"myimage:v1.0.0\"`\n\n#### Scenario 3.3: Build image with build arguments\n- **GIVEN** a Dockerfile that expects build arguments\n- **WHEN** `build_image(..., build_args={\"HTTP_PROXY\": \"http://proxy.example.com:8080\", \"HTTPS_PROXY\": \"https://proxy.example.com:8080\"})` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Pass the build arguments to Docker during build\n  - Use them for dependency resolution during the build process\n\n#### Scenario 3.4: Build success with verbose logging\n- **GIVEN** `verbose=True` when creating `DockerService`\n- **WHEN** `build_image()` successfully completes\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Log each build step as it progresses\n  - Log final success message with image details\n\n#### Scenario 3.5: Build failure with invalid Dockerfile\n- **GIVEN** an invalid Dockerfile with syntax errors\n- **WHEN** `build_image()` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Raise an appropriate exception (e.g., `BuildError` or `docker.errors.BuildError`)\n  - Include descriptive error message about the build failure\n  - Log build error details if verbose is enabled\n\n#### Scenario 3.6: Build failure with missing Dockerfile\n- **GIVEN** a dockerfile_path that does not exist\n- **WHEN** `build_image()` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Raise a `FileNotFoundError` or `ValueError`\n  - Include the missing file path in the error message\n\n#### Scenario 3.7: Build failure with missing context directory\n- **GIVEN** a context_path that does not exist\n- **WHEN** `build_image()` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Raise a `FileNotFoundError` or `ValueError`\n  - Include the missing directory path in the error message\n\n---\n\n## REQ-004: Docker image information retrieval\n\n### Requirement: Retrieve detailed image information\n\nSystem SHALL provide methods to retrieve metadata about Docker images.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Returns image ID, size, creation time, and tags\n- Formats size in human-readable format\n- Handles non-existent images appropriately\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n#### Scenario 4.1: Get info for existing image\n- **GIVEN** a Docker image exists locally with name `\"myimage:latest\"`\n- **WHEN** `get_image_info(\"myimage:latest\")` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL return a dict containing:\n  - `image_id`: the SHA256 hash of the image\n  - `image_size`: human-readable format (e.g., \"2.0 GB\" or \"2 GiB\")\n  - `created`: ISO 8601 timestamp\n  - `tags`: list of tags associated with the image\n\n#### Scenario 4.2: Format size in human-readable format\n- **GIVEN** an image size of 2147483648 bytes (2 GB)\n- **WHEN** the system formats the size\n- **THEN** the result SHALL be one of:\n  - `\"2.0 GB\"` (decimal format)\n  - `\"2.0 GiB\"` (binary format)\n  - Consistent format must be used throughout\n\n#### Scenario 4.3: Get info for image without tag (defaults to latest)\n- **GIVEN** a Docker image exists with name `\"myimage\"` and tag `\"latest\"`\n- **WHEN** `get_image_info(\"myimage\")` is called (without tag)\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Look for the `\"latest\"` tag\n  - Return information for `myimage:latest`\n\n#### Scenario 4.4: Get info for non-existent image\n- **GIVEN** an image name `\"nonexistent:latest\"` that does not exist locally\n- **WHEN** `get_image_info(\"nonexistent:latest\")` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Raise an appropriate exception (e.g., `ImageNotFoundError`)\n  - Include descriptive message indicating the image was not found\n\n#### Scenario 4.5: Get info with verbose logging\n- **GIVEN** `verbose=True` when creating `DockerService`\n- **WHEN** `get_image_info()` successfully retrieves image information\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Log the retrieval operation\n  - Log the image details\n\n---\n\n## REQ-005: Docker image pushing to registry\n\n### Requirement: Push images to container registries\n\nSystem SHALL provide a method to push Docker images to container registries with optional authentication.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Supports public and private registries\n- Handles authentication when credentials provided\n- Re-tags images for registry push when needed\n- Streams push progress in real-time\n- Returns push result information\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n#### Scenario 5.1: Push image without authentication to public registry\n- **GIVEN** a local image `\"myimage:latest\"` exists\n- **AND** a public registry URL `\"registry.example.com/username\"`\n- **WHEN** `push_image(image_name=\"myimage\", registry_url=\"registry.example.com/username\")` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Re-tag the image to `\"registry.example.com/username/myimage:latest\"`\n  - Push the image to the registry without authentication\n  - Return a dict containing:\n    - `pushed_image`: `\"registry.example.com/username/myimage:latest\"`\n    - `push_time`: ISO 8601 timestamp\n\n#### Scenario 5.2: Push image with authentication to private registry\n- **GIVEN** a local image exists\n- **AND** a private registry requiring credentials\n- **WHEN** `push_image(image_name=\"myimage\", registry_url=\"registry.example.com/username\", username=\"myuser\", password=\"mypass\")` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Authenticate with the registry using provided credentials\n  - Re-tag the image for the registry\n  - Push the authenticated image\n  - Return push result information\n\n#### Scenario 5.3: Push image with tag specification\n- **GIVEN** a local image `\"myimage:v1.0.0\"` exists\n- **WHEN** `push_image(image_name=\"myimage:v1.0.0\", registry_url=\"registry.example.com/username\")` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Re-tag to `\"registry.example.com/username/myimage:v1.0.0\"`\n  - Push the specific tagged version\n\n#### Scenario 5.4: Push with verbose logging\n- **GIVEN** `verbose=True` when creating `DockerService`\n- **WHEN** `push_image()` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Log authentication step if applicable\n  - Log re-tagging operation\n  - Stream and log push progress for each layer\n\n#### Scenario 5.5: Push failure due to authentication error\n- **GIVEN** invalid credentials for a private registry\n- **WHEN** `push_image()` attempts to authenticate and push\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Raise an authentication exception\n  - Include descriptive error message about authentication failure\n  - NOT store or log the password\n\n#### Scenario 5.6: Push failure due to network issues\n- **GIVEN** network connectivity issues or unreachable registry\n- **WHEN** `push_image()` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Raise a network-related exception\n  - Include descriptive error message about the connection failure\n\n#### Scenario 5.7: Push failure due to non-existent local image\n- **GIVEN** an image name that does not exist locally\n- **WHEN** `push_image()` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Raise an exception indicating the image was not found\n  - Include the image name in the error message\n\n---\n\n## REQ-006: Docker image removal\n\n### Requirement: Remove Docker images from local daemon\n\nSystem SHALL provide a method to remove Docker images from the local Docker daemon.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Removes existing images successfully\n- Returns boolean indicating success/failure\n- Handles non-existent images gracefully\n- Supports force removal option\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n#### Scenario 6.1: Remove existing image\n- **GIVEN** a Docker image `\"myimage:latest\"` exists locally\n- **WHEN** `remove_image(\"myimage:latest\")` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Remove the image from local Docker daemon\n  - Return `True`\n  - Log removal operation if verbose is enabled\n\n#### Scenario 6.2: Remove non-existent image\n- **GIVEN** an image name `\"nonexistent:latest\"` that does not exist locally\n- **WHEN** `remove_image(\"nonexistent:latest\")` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Return `False`\n  - Log a warning message if verbose is enabled\n  - NOT raise an exception\n\n#### Scenario 6.3: Force remove image in use\n- **GIVEN** an image that has dependent containers or is in use\n- **WHEN** `remove_image(\"myimage:latest\", force=True)` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Attempt to force-remove the image\n  - Return `True` if successful\n  - Return `False` if removal still fails\n  - Log the operation if verbose is enabled\n\n#### Scenario 6.4: Remove image without force (fails when in use)\n- **GIVEN** an image that has dependent containers\n- **WHEN** `remove_image(\"myimage:latest\")` is called without force option\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Return `False`\n  - Log a warning message if verbose is enabled\n  - NOT raise an exception\n\n---\n\n## REQ-007: Docker registry authentication\n\n### Requirement: Authenticate with Docker registries\n\nSystem SHALL provide methods to authenticate with Docker registries using username/password credentials.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Authenticates with specified registry URL\n- Supports Docker Hub as default registry\n- Handles authentication failures appropriately\n- Does not store passwords in logs\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n#### Scenario 7.1: Login to private registry\n- **GIVEN** valid credentials for a private registry\n- **WHEN** `_docker_login_sdk(registry_url=\"registry.example.com\", username=\"myuser\", password=\"mypass\")` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Use Docker SDK to authenticate with the specified registry\n  - Return success or raise exception on failure\n  - NOT log or store the password\n\n#### Scenario 7.2: Login to Docker Hub (default registry)\n- **GIVEN** valid Docker Hub credentials\n- **WHEN** `_docker_login_sdk(registry_url=None, username=\"myuser\", password=\"mypass\")` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Authenticate with Docker Hub (default registry)\n  - Return success or raise exception on failure\n\n#### Scenario 7.3: Authentication failure with invalid credentials\n- **GIVEN** invalid credentials for a registry\n- **WHEN** `_docker_login_sdk()` is called with invalid credentials\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Raise an authentication exception\n  - Include descriptive error message about authentication failure\n\n#### Scenario 7.4: Authentication failure with unreachable registry\n- **GIVEN** credentials but registry is unreachable\n- **WHEN** `_docker_login_sdk()` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Raise a network-related exception\n  - Include descriptive error message about connection failure\n\n---\n\n## REQ-008: Docker image tagging\n\n### Requirement: Tag Docker images for registry\n\nSystem SHALL provide methods to tag Docker images with new names or repository paths.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Tags images for registry push\n- Handles multiple tags\n- Validates source image exists\n- Handles tagging failures\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n#### Scenario 8.1: Tag image for registry\n- **GIVEN** a local image `\"myimage:latest\"` exists\n- **WHEN** `_tag_image_sdk(source_image=\"myimage:latest\", target_image=\"registry.example.com/username/myimage:v1.0\")` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Create a new tag for the image\n  - Point to the specified registry path\n  - Return success\n\n#### Scenario 8.2: Tag non-existent source image\n- **GIVEN** a source image that does not exist\n- **WHEN** `_tag_image_sdk(source_image=\"nonexistent:latest\", target_image=\"registry.example.com/username/myimage:v1.0\")` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Raise an exception with descriptive message\n  - Indicate that the source image was not found\n\n#### Scenario 8.3: Tag image with invalid target format\n- **GIVEN** a valid source image\n- **WHEN** `_tag_image_sdk(source_image=\"myimage:latest\", target_image=\"invalid:image:name:format\")` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Raise an exception or return failure\n  - Indicate invalid image name format\n\n---\n\n## REQ-009: Verbose logging and error reporting\n\n### Requirement: Consistent verbose logging across operations\n\nSystem SHALL provide consistent verbose logging and meaningful error messages for all Docker operations.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Logs operation progress when verbose is enabled\n- Provides descriptive error messages for all failures\n- Uses appropriate log levels (info, warning, error)\n- Does not expose sensitive information in logs\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n#### Scenario 9.1: Verbose logging during build\n- **GIVEN** `verbose=True` when creating `DockerService`\n- **WHEN** `build_image()` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Log build start message with image name\n  - Log each build step as it progresses\n  - Log final success message with image ID and size\n  - Log build error details if build fails\n\n#### Scenario 9.2: Verbose logging during push\n- **GIVEN** `verbose=True` and an image push operation\n- **WHEN** `push_image()` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Log authentication step (without password)\n  - Log re-tagging operation\n  - Log push progress for each layer being transferred\n  - Log final success message with pushed image name\n\n#### Scenario 9.3: Descriptive error messages\n- **GIVEN** any Docker operation fails\n- **WHEN** an exception is raised\n- **THEN** the exception message SHALL include:\n  - The operation that failed (build, push, remove, etc.)\n  - The image name involved\n  - The root cause of the failure\n\n#### Scenario 9.4: No sensitive information in logs\n- **GIVEN** an operation involving credentials (e.g., push with password)\n- **WHEN** verbose logging is enabled\n- **THEN** the logs SHALL:\n  - NOT contain the password in plain text\n  - Use placeholders like `******` or `[REDACTED]` for sensitive values\n\n#### Scenario 9.5: Silent operation without verbose logging\n- **GIVEN** `verbose=False` when creating `DockerService`\n- **WHEN** any Docker operation is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - NOT log operation progress\n  - Only raise exceptions on failures (not log them)\n\n---\n\n## REQ-010: Input validation and parameter handling\n\n### Requirement: Validate all input parameters\n\nSystem SHALL validate all input parameters before initiating Docker operations.\n\n**Acceptance Criteria:**\n- Validates file paths exist\n- Validates parameter types and formats\n- Provides clear error messages for invalid inputs\n- Handles edge cases gracefully\n\n**Scenarios:**\n\n#### Scenario 10.1: Validate dockerfile_path exists\n- **GIVEN** a dockerfile_path that does not exist\n- **WHEN** `build_image()` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Raise `FileNotFoundError` or `ValueError`\n  - Include the missing file path in the error message\n\n#### Scenario 10.2: Validate context_path exists and is directory\n- **GIVEN** a context_path that does not exist or is not a directory\n- **WHEN** `build_image()` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Raise appropriate exception\n  - Include the invalid path in the error message\n\n#### Scenario 10.3: Validate image_name format\n- **GIVEN** an invalid image_name format (e.g., contains spaces or special characters)\n- **WHEN** any operation is called with this image_name\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Validate the image name format\n  - Raise exception with message about invalid format\n  - Reference Docker naming conventions\n\n#### Scenario 10.4: Validate build_args is dict\n- **GIVEN** build_args parameter is not a dictionary\n- **WHEN** `build_image()` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Raise `TypeError` or `ValueError`\n  - Indicate that build_args must be a dictionary\n\n#### Scenario 10.5: Validate tag format\n- **GIVEN** an invalid tag format (e.g., contains invalid characters)\n- **WHEN** an operation is called with this tag\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Validate the tag format\n  - Raise exception with message about invalid tag format\n\n---\n\n## Non-Functional Requirements\n\n### Performance\n\n#### NFR-001: Operation completion time\n- `check_docker_available()` SHALL complete within 5 seconds\n- `build_image()` SHALL stream build logs in real-time and not buffer entire output before returning on error\n- `push_image()` SHALL stream push progress and handle large images efficiently\n- `get_image_info()` SHALL complete within 2 seconds for typical images\n\n#### NFR-002: Resource usage\n- The service SHALL handle large images (multi-GB) without excessive memory usage\n- Build and push operations SHALL use streaming to avoid loading entire artifacts into memory\n\n### Reliability\n\n#### NFR-003: Error handling\n- The service SHALL handle temporary network failures during push operations with appropriate error messages\n- The service SHALL validate input parameters before initiating Docker operations\n- The service SHALL use Docker SDK's built-in retry mechanisms where applicable\n- The service SHALL not crash on Docker daemon restarts\n\n#### NFR-004: State management\n- The service SHALL be stateless between method calls\n- Docker client SHALL be re-initialized if daemon becomes unavailable\n\n### Maintainability\n\n#### NFR-005: Code organization\n- The service SHALL encapsulate Docker SDK complexity behind a clean, high-level API\n- Private methods SHALL start with underscore to indicate internal use\n- The service SHALL not leak Docker SDK exceptions directly to callers without appropriate wrapping\n- The service SHALL follow Python type hints where appropriate\n\n#### NFR-006: Documentation\n- All public methods SHALL have docstrings\n- Docstrings SHALL include parameter types, return types, and raise information\n- Error messages SHALL be actionable and reference documentation when applicable\n\n### Security\n\n#### NFR-007: Credential handling\n- Passwords SHALL NOT be logged or stored in instance variables\n- Authentication SHALL use secure methods provided by Docker SDK\n- The service SHALL support environment variable-based authentication\n\n#### NFR-008: Path validation\n- The service SHALL validate file paths to prevent directory traversal attacks\n- The service SHALL restrict operations to authorized directories\n\n---\n\n## Integration Scenarios\n\n### INT-001: Build and push workflow\n\n#### Scenario INT-1.1: Complete build and push cycle\n- **GIVEN** a valid agent workspace with Dockerfile\n- **WHEN** the user runs:\n  1. `build_image()` to create local image\n  2. `get_image_info()` to verify build\n  3. `push_image()` to publish to registry\n- **THEN** each operation SHALL:\n  - Complete successfully\n  - Return appropriate result information\n  - Log progress if verbose is enabled\n\n#### Scenario INT-1.2: Build with proxy and push to private registry\n- **GIVEN** a workspace behind an HTTP proxy\n- **AND** a private registry requiring authentication\n- **WHEN** the user runs:\n  1. `build_image(build_args={\"HTTP_PROXY\": \"proxy_url\"})` \n  2. `push_image(username=\"user\", password=\"pass\", registry_url=\"private.registry.com\")`\n- **THEN** the operations SHALL:\n  - Use proxy for dependency resolution during build\n  - Authenticate and push to private registry\n\n### INT-002: Error recovery workflows\n\n#### Scenario INT-2.1: Retry after transient network failure\n- **GIVEN** a push operation fails due to transient network error\n- **WHEN** the user retries `push_image()`\n- **THEN** the operation SHALL:\n  - Succeed on retry if network is restored\n  - NOT require re-authentication if credentials were valid\n\n#### Scenario INT-2.2: Rebuild after Dockerfile changes\n- **GIVEN** an initial successful build\n- **WHEN** the Dockerfile is modified and `build_image()` is called again\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Rebuild the image with new Dockerfile\n  - Create a new image with updated content\n  - Return new image ID\n\n---\n\n## Edge Cases and Error Conditions\n\n### EDGE-001: Docker daemon issues\n\n#### Scenario EDGE-1.1: Docker daemon restart during operation\n- **GIVEN** a long-running build operation\n- **WHEN** Docker daemon restarts during build\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Raise an appropriate exception\n  - Include message about daemon availability\n\n#### Scenario EDGE-1.2: Insufficient disk space\n- **GIVEN** limited disk space on host\n- **WHEN** `build_image()` runs out of disk space\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Raise an appropriate exception\n  - Include message about disk space\n\n### EDGE-002: Image naming conflicts\n\n#### Scenario EDGE-2.1: Image with same name and tag already exists\n- **GIVEN** an image `\"myimage:latest\"` already exists locally\n- **WHEN** `build_image(image_name=\"myimage\")` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Overwrite the existing image\n  - Return new image information\n\n#### Scenario EDGE-2.2: Multiple tags for same image ID\n- **GIVEN** an image with ID `abc123` has tags `latest` and `v1.0`\n- **WHEN** `remove_image(\"myimage:latest\")` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Remove only the `latest` tag\n  - Keep the `v1.0` tag and image content\n\n### EDGE-003: Registry-specific issues\n\n#### Scenario EDGE-3.1: Registry rate limiting\n- **GIVEN** a registry with rate limits\n- **WHEN** `push_image()` encounters rate limiting\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Raise an appropriate exception\n  - Include message about rate limiting\n\n#### Scenario EDGE-3.2: Registry with self-signed certificate\n- **GIVEN** a registry using self-signed certificate\n- **WHEN** `push_image()` attempts to push\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Raise a certificate-related exception\n  - Include message about certificate validation\n\n---\n\n## Technical Constraints\n\n### Requirement: Language and dependencies\n\nSystem SHALL use Python 3.10+ and the following dependencies:\n\n**Dependencies:**\n- `docker>=6.0.0` for Docker SDK\n- `python-dateutil>=2.8.0` for timestamp handling (optional, can use datetime)\n- Standard library: `pathlib`, `logging`, `typing`, `datetime`\n\n### Requirement: File locations\n\n- DockerService implementation: `agentcube/services/docker_service.py`\n- Used by: `BuildRuntime` and `PublishRuntime`\n\n### Requirement: Docker API version\n\nThe service SHALL:\n- Use Docker API version compatible with Docker SDK 6.0.0+\n- Support both Docker Engine and Docker Desktop environments\n- Handle API version mismatches gracefully\n\n### Requirement: Exception hierarchy\n\nThe service SHALL define and use appropriate exception types:\n- Custom exceptions for service-specific errors\n- Wrapping of Docker SDK exceptions\n- Clear exception hierarchy for callers to catch appropriately\n\n---\n\n## Testing Requirements\n\n### Unit Test Scenarios\n\n#### Scenario UT-1.1: Test DockerService initialization\n- **GIVEN** a test suite for DockerService\n- **WHEN** tests run\n- **THEN** tests SHALL cover:\n  - Initialization with verbose=True\n  - Initialization with verbose=False\n  - Initialization failure handling\n\n#### Scenario UT-1.2: Test Docker availability checking\n- **GIVEN** a test suite for availability checking\n- **WHEN** tests run\n- **THEN** tests SHALL cover:\n  - Available Docker daemon returns True\n  - Unavailable Docker daemon returns False\n  - Client not initialized returns False\n\n#### Scenario UT-1.3: Test image building\n- **GIVEN** a test suite for image building\n- **WHEN** tests run\n- **THEN** tests SHALL cover:\n  - Build with default tag\n  - Build with custom tag\n  - Build with build arguments\n  - Build failure with invalid Dockerfile\n  - Build failure with missing files\n  - Verbose logging during build\n\n#### Scenario UT-1.4: Test image information retrieval\n- **GIVEN** a test suite for image info\n- **WHEN** tests run\n- **THEN** tests SHALL cover:\n  - Get info for existing image\n  - Size formatting\n  - Get info for non-existent image\n  - Image without tag defaults to latest\n\n#### Scenario UT-1.5: Test image pushing\n- **GIVEN** a test suite for image pushing\n- **WHEN** tests run\n- **THEN** tests SHALL cover:\n  - Push without authentication\n  - Push with authentication\n  - Push with custom tag\n  - Push failure due to authentication\n  - Push failure due to network issues\n  - Verbose logging during push\n\n#### Scenario UT-1.6: Test image removal\n- **GIVEN** a test suite for image removal\n- **WHEN** tests run\n- **THEN** tests SHALL cover:\n  - Remove existing image\n  - Remove non-existent image\n  - Force remove image in use\n  - Verbose logging during removal\n\n#### Scenario UT-1.7: Test authentication\n- **GIVEN** a test suite for authentication\n- **WHEN** tests run\n- **THEN** tests SHALL cover:\n  - Login to private registry\n  - Login to Docker Hub\n  - Authentication failure handling\n  - Password not logged\n\n#### Scenario UT-1.8: Test image tagging\n- **GIVEN** a test suite for image tagging\n- **WHEN** tests run\n- **THEN** tests SHALL cover:\n  - Tag image for registry\n  - Tag non-existent source image\n  - Invalid target format\n\n#### Scenario UT-1.9: Test input validation\n- **GIVEN** a test suite for input validation\n- **WHEN** tests run\n- **THEN** tests SHALL cover:\n  - Validate dockerfile_path exists\n  - Validate context_path exists\n  - Validate image_name format\n  - Validate build_args type\n  - Validate tag format\n\n### Integration Test Scenarios\n\n#### Scenario IT-1.1: End-to-end build and push\n- **GIVEN** a valid Dockerfile and build context\n- **WHEN** the full workflow runs:\n  1. `build_image()`\n  2. `get_image_info()`\n  3. `push_image()`\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Complete all operations successfully\n  - Return correct result information\n\n#### Scenario IT-1.2: Build with proxy configuration\n- **GIVEN** a workspace requiring proxy for dependencies\n- **WHEN** `build_image(build_args={\"HTTP_PROXY\": \"proxy_url\"})` is called\n- **THEN** the system SHALL:\n  - Successfully build with proxy configuration\n  - Verify dependencies were resolved through proxy\n\n### Mock Test Scenarios\n\n#### Scenario MT-1.1: Mock Docker client for unit tests\n- **GIVEN** unit tests that should not require actual Docker daemon\n- **WHEN** tests run\n- **THEN** tests SHALL:\n  - Mock Docker SDK client\n  - Test service logic without Docker dependency\n  - Verify correct method calls and parameters\n\n---\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n### Functional Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] DockerService initializes with optional verbose logging\n- [ ] check_docker_available() returns correct availability status\n- [ ] build_image() successfully builds images with default and custom tags\n- [ ] build_image() accepts and applies build arguments\n- [ ] build_image() streams build logs in real-time\n- [ ] get_image_info() returns correct image metadata\n- [ ] get_image_info() formats size in human-readable format\n- [ ] push_image() successfully pushes to public and private registries\n- [ ] push_image() handles authentication properly without exposing passwords\n- [ ] push_image() re-tags images for registry when needed\n- [ ] remove_image() removes existing images and returns appropriate status\n- [ ] remove_image() handles non-existent images gracefully\n- [ ] _docker_login_sdk() authenticates with registries correctly\n- [ ] _tag_image_sdk() tags images correctly\n- [ ] Verbose logging works across all operations\n- [ ] All error paths provide meaningful error messages\n- [ ] Input validation is performed for all parameters\n- [ ] Sensitive information (passwords) is not logged\n\n### Non-Functional Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] check_docker_available() completes within 5 seconds\n- [ ] build_image() streams logs in real-time\n- [ ] push_image() streams progress efficiently\n- [ ] get_image_info() completes within 2 seconds for typical images\n- [ ] Service handles large images without excessive memory usage\n- [ ] Service handles temporary network failures gracefully\n- [ ] Service validates inputs before Docker operations\n- [ ] Private methods start with underscore\n- [ ] Public methods have docstrings\n- [ ] Error messages are actionable\n- [ ] Unit tests cover all major code paths\n- [ ] Integration tests cover end-to-end workflows\n- [ ] Mock tests allow testing without Docker daemon\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Notes\n\n### Key Components\n\n1. **DockerService** (`agentcube/services/docker_service.py`)\n   - Main service class implementing all Docker operations\n   - Encapsulates Docker SDK complexity\n   - Provides high-level API for build, push, remove operations\n\n2. **Docker SDK Integration**\n   - Uses `docker.from_env()` for client initialization\n   - Leverages Docker SDK's built-in streaming for build/push\n   - Handles Docker SDK exceptions appropriately\n\n3. **Logging Infrastructure**\n   - Uses Python's `logging` module\n   - Supports verbose mode for detailed output\n   - Protects sensitive information from logs\n\n### Key Algorithms\n\n#### Build Image Algorithm\n1. Validate dockerfile_path exists\n2. Validate context_path exists and is directory\n3. Validate image_name format\n4. Set build arguments from build_args parameter\n5. Call Docker SDK's images.build() with:\n   - path=context_path\n   - dockerfile=dockerfile_path\n   - tag=f\"{image_name}:{tag}\"\n   - buildargs=build_args\n6. Stream build logs if verbose\n7. Extract image ID and size\n8. Format size in human-readable format\n9. Return result dict\n\n#### Push Image Algorithm\n1. Validate image_name exists locally\n2. If registry_url is provided:\n   - Authenticate if username/password provided\n   - Re-tag image for registry: f\"{registry_url}/{image_name}\"\n3. Call Docker SDK's images.push() with:\n   - repository=full_image_name\n   - tag=tag\n4. Stream push logs if verbose\n5. Return result dict with pushed_image and push_time\n\n#### Get Image Info Algorithm\n1. Call Docker SDK's images.get() with image_name\n2. Extract image_id from image.attrs['Id']\n3. Calculate size from image.attrs['Size']\n4. Format size in human-readable format\n5. Extract creation time from image.attrs['Created']\n6. Extract tags from image.attrs['RepoTags']\n7. Return result dict\n\n#### Remove Image Algorithm\n1. Call Docker SDK's images.remove() with:\n   - image=image_name\n   - force=force parameter\n2. Return True if successful\n3. Catch ImageNotFound exception and return False\n4. Log warning if verbose is enabled\n\n### Exception Handling Strategy\n\n1. **Docker SDK Exceptions**: Wrap in service-specific exceptions\n2. **File System Exceptions**: Preserve and add context\n3. **Network Exceptions**: Add retry information to message\n4. **Validation Exceptions**: Include parameter details\n\n### Logging Strategy\n\n1. **Verbose Mode**: Log all operations with details\n2. **Non-Verbose Mode**: Only log errors\n3. **Sensitive Data**: Never log passwords or tokens\n4. **Log Levels**: Use appropriate levels (INFO, WARNING, ERROR)\n\n---\n\n## Related Requirements\n\n- **AR-021:** CLI build command (consumes DockerService)\n- **AR-022:** CLI publish command (consumes DockerService)\n- **cli-toolkit/design.md:** Base design for DockerService\n- **cli-toolkit/spec.md:** Base specifications for Docker integration\n- **docker>=6.0.0:** Docker SDK documentation\n\n---\n\n## Notes\n\n- The `DockerService` SHALL use `docker.from_env()` to initialize the Docker client\n- All file paths SHALL be validated to exist before Docker operations\n- Image names and tags SHALL follow Docker naming conventions\n- The service SHALL be thread-safe for concurrent read operations\n- Timeout configurations should be considered for long-running build and push operations\n- The service SHOULD support environment variables for Docker configuration (DOCKER_HOST, etc.)\n- Consider adding timeout parameters to long-running operations\n- Consider adding dry-run mode for testing without actual Docker operations","filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-024/delta-spec.md"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-024/delta-spec.md","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-024/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775870920038,"end":1775870920048}}}}
